It is a very powerful compiler And, we are going to use it, like I said, mainly through make files, but if you want to actually, compile a program using GCC, it's pretty simple. I have a little hello world program, called hello dot c. If I type g c c hello dot c then enter, it compiles my program. But basically you run the program by saying dot slash which says in the current directory run a dot out and it will say hello world. So that's the the very basic, way to run g c c and if you always want your output files to called a dot out, that's how you do it. But, of course, you can you can tell it to put your, file in a different name. You can actually put the the program in different name. We can type gcc hello dot c dash o hello and it will put the file in, put the program in a file called hello. Great. You have to be very careful with this dash o. If you typed the following, we said g c c hello dot c dash o hello dot c. A lot of people do that just because they're not necessarily thinking about it. So for instance, let me make a copy here, copy hello dot c to hello dot backup and let's try this, gcc hello dot c dash oh hello dot c and it goes oh sure and then you go dot slash hello dot c you go oh it's a binary file and if we look at it hello dot if we go let's go change our program hello dot c it ends up as this binary garbage that we can't get through and we have no way to get back to our original program. Let's say we forget the semicolon at the end of this line, something like that. And if we do gcc hello. C, it will say, oh, guess what, in function main we had an error, we forgot a semicolon. It says there expected semicolon before the return zero and we go back and we fix it. And this does not create an executable. If it doesn't know how to compile it, it won't create the executable. If you get an error and there is still an executable and you say, hey, wait a minute, it does work. It's the old executable, not your new one. So if you get errors, you'd know that you did not produce a, did not produce the correct, an actual output file. Now you could get warnings and no errors and it will produce a file but remember in CS107 we should try to compile our code with no warnings. So that's that, let's go fix it. Go back up and we add that and then we compile it again, there we go. Now it's compiled just fine. Now what other flags are there? What other options are there? So those are the big things. The other one that we're gonna do is going to be dash t d equals gnu 99 which means, there's a particular flavor of c that we're going to be using in the class and, it's called the, c 99 and the gnu flavor of c 99 is the one we're gonna use. Standard that that allows you to do things like put define integers inside your for loop expression and so forth. So we're gonna use that. And then hello dot c dash o hello and there you go. Okay. So now it, that compiled it just fine. So there's tons of different flags you can use. We have plenty in the make file, but, this is how you run GCC on your own if you just want to quickly compile a file. Thanks.
